    "narrative": "Ghost Ride the WHIP enters April 12 with a clear hierarchy of efficiency, led by **Corbin Carroll**, who commands the day's highest score at 80.85. His position at the top of the lineup combined with a favorable matchup against Pop and a massive 0.372 xwOBA ceiling makes him the cornerstone of today\u2019s offensive strategy. **Josh Naylor** (69.07) and **Trevor Story** (67.13) follow as our strongest ancillary plays; **Trevor Story** specifically benefits from an ideal confluence of high-speed base-stealing potential against a slow-working pitcher and favorable wind conditions that help mitigate his neutral platoon standing. Meanwhile, **Mickey Moniak** (64.99) and **Brice Turang** (66.23) continue to offer excellent value, with **Mickey Moniak** reaping the benefits of a prime #3 spot and a significant platoon edge that has effectively neutralized the threat posed by Pivetta.\n\nThe bench decision process was tightly contested between **Zach McKinstry** (49.24) and **Seiya Suzuki** (49.75), with the latter ultimately winning the start. While **Zach McKinstry** boasts elite sprint speed metrics that would typically vault him into consideration, his projection was hampered by an unfavorable #8 lineup spot, whereas **Seiya Suzuki** is bolstered by favorable wind conditions and a middle-of-the-order opportunity despite the tough draw against Chandler. We have exercised caution elsewhere, specifically with **Dalton Rushing**, whose efficiency (42.64) is severely tempered by a daunting matchup against deGrom; he remains active, but our expectations are lowered. Owners should also note the risk associated with **James Wood** (51.65); while his 100% stolen base delivery rating against Woodruff is elite, the low 2.90 xERA of his opposing starter keeps him firmly in the \"marginal\" tier, serving as a reminder that we are prioritizing game-cap preservation in high-difficulty matchups across the board.",
